<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41096b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41096b">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41096b"> 96(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> a wife told / me</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[<font size="-1">THINGS HEARD AND SEEN</font>]</font> In the <cite>Spiritual Diary</cite> <font color="green">[of E.S.]</font> &hellip; there is a charming picture of a place of training for maidens <font color="green">[in Heaven]</font>: &ldquo;&hellip; They receive their garments gratis, not knowing how, which they put on daily, having better ones for festivals. They also have little gardens; and so long as they are virgins, there are only flowers there, and not fruits until they become wives. When they see spots on their garments, it is a sign that they have had evil thoughts; and that they have done something wrong; these spots cannot be washed out &hellip; and if they themselves do not know what it is <font color="green">[that they have done wrong]</font>, <mark>a wife comes who tells them</mark>.&rdquo; <small> George Trobridge, <a name="GTLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#GTLS"><cite title="source">A Life of Emanuel Swedenborg</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (??) 200 [204]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
